New Mexican cuisine is a distinct regional culinary tradition hailing from the [Southwestern](/Cuisine_of_the_Southwestern_United_States) [US](/United_States_of_America) [state](/U.S._state) of [New Mexico](/New_Mexico). It’s a fascinating tapestry woven from the threads of [Pueblo](/Pueblo) [Native American cuisine](/Native_American_cuisine) and the rich heritage of [Hispano](/Hispanos_of_New_Mexico) [Spanish](/Spanish_cuisine) and [Mexican](/Mexican_cuisine) culinary practices, all rooted deeply in the historical expanse of [Nuevo México](/Santa_Fe_de_Nuevo_M%C3%A9xico). This unique Southwestern flavor profile doesn't confine itself to the current borders of New Mexico; its influence radiates outward, permeating the old territories of Nuevo México and the [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory). You'll find its echoes in [Arizona](/Arizona), swathes of [Texas](/Texas) (specifically [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) and [the Panhandle](/Texas_panhandle)), and even in the southern reaches of [Colorado](/Colorado), [Utah](/Utah), and [Nevada](/Nevada). More than just a geographic marker, New Mexican cuisine is recognized globally, particularly by those who identify with [Oasisamerican](/Oasisamerican), [Hispano](/Hispanos_of_New_Mexico) heritage, [caballero](/Vaquero) [cowboy culture](/Cowboy_culture), or simply anyone with a connection to the Land of Enchantment.

The journey of New Mexican cuisine is a testament to its diverse influences. In its nascent stages, it was shaped by the indigenous Pueblo people, alongside the culinary practices of the neighboring [Apache](/Apache) and [Navajo](/Eating_culture_of_the_Navajo_Nation) peoples, and the broader culinary traditions of [New Spain](/New_Spain) and the [Spanish Empire](/Spanish_Empire). Later, influences from [French](/French_cuisine), [Italian](/Italian_cuisine), [Portuguese](/Portuguese_cuisine), and other [Mediterranean cuisines](/Mediterranean_cuisine) introduced new ingredients and techniques, enriching the existing palette. The era of early European settlement added its own charm with the emergence of [bed and breakfasts](/Bed_and_breakfast) and [cafés](/Caf%C3%A9). The American territorial period left its mark through cowboy [chuckwagons](/Chuckwagon) and the vibrant atmosphere of [Western saloons](/Western_saloon). This was followed by the quintessentially American [diner](/Diner) culture that flourished along [Route 66](/U.S._Route_66), the influx of [Mexican-American cuisine](/Mexican-American_cuisine), the rise of fast food, and the integration of [global culinary trends](/Global_cuisine) after New Mexico achieved statehood in 1912.

Despite this rich confluence of cultures, New Mexican cuisine largely evolved in splendid isolation, steadfastly preserving its indigenous, Spanish, Mexican, and Latin roots. This has resulted in a culinary identity that stands apart from other [Latin American cuisines](/Latin_American_cuisine) found within the [contiguous United States](/Contiguous_United_States). Its true distinction lies in its unwavering focus on local spices, herbs, flavors, and vegetables. Paramount among these are the iconic red and green [New Mexico chile](/New_Mexico_chile) peppers, the subtle sweetness of [anise](/Anise)—a key component in the beloved [biscochitos](/Bizcochito)—and the earthy richness of [piñon](/Pine_nuts), enjoyed as a snack or incorporated into delectable desserts.

Signature dishes that embody the soul of New Mexico include Native American [frybread](/Frybread)-style [sopapillas](/Sopapilla), hearty [breakfast burritos](/Breakfast_burrito), the layered decadence of [enchilada](/Enchilada) montada (stacked enchiladas), warming green chile stew, [carne seca](/Carne_seca) (a uniquely thin, dried jerky), robust green chile burgers, comforting [posole](/Pozole) (a hominy-based stew), slow-cooked frijoles (typically [pinto](/Pinto_bean) or [bolita](/Bolita_bean) beans), the vibrant [calabacitas](/Calabacitas) (a sautéed dish of [zucchini](/Zucchini) and [summer squash](/Summer_squash)), and the deeply flavorful [carne adobada](/Adobada) (pork marinated in red chile).

### History

Before the current boundaries of New Mexico were established, the vast territory of [Santa Fe de Nuevo México](/Santa_Fe_de_Nuevo_M%C3%A9xico) encompassed the lands of the [Pueblo](/Pueblo) peoples, as well as territories claimed by the [Chiricahua](/Chiricahua), [Comanche](/Comanche), [Mescalero](/Mescalero), and [Navajo](/Navajo_people).

The arrival of the Spaniards introduced their own culinary traditions, which soon mingled with those of the indigenous populations. They brought with them ingredients such as wheat, rice, and various meats like beef and mutton/lamb, which were integrated with the native corn, chile, beans, and squash, creating a new culinary landscape. This period of early development saw the widespread adoption of the [horno](/Horno), a distinctive outdoor beehive-shaped [earth oven](/Earth_oven), which became a fixture in both [Pueblo](/Puebloan_peoples) and [Hispano](/Hispanos_of_New_Mexico) communities. This unique historical trajectory, coupled with the specific terrain and climate of the region, has resulted in significant divergences between New Mexican cuisine and similar styles found in [Northern Mexico](/Northern_Mexico) and other [Southwestern US states](/Southwestern_United_States) like [California](/California), [Arizona](/Arizona), and [Texas](/Texas).

New Mexico's population has always been a rich blend of cultures. Native Americans, including the [Ancestral Pueblo](/Ancestral_Pueblo) peoples and the modern [Pueblo](/Pueblo), [Navajo](/Navajo), and [Apache](/Apache) nations, have cultivated the land for millennia. The [Hispano](/Hispanos_of_New_Mexico) explorers, farmers, and ranchers arrived during the Spanish colonial era in the 16th century and continued through the Mexican period, which concluded in the 19th century. Following the American Civil War, Americans began to settle and trade in the region, and in more recent times, communities from Asia and other parts of the world have added their own flavors to the New Mexican culinary mosaic.

When New Mexicans speak of "chile," they are referring to the pungent pods themselves or the sauce made from them, not the spiced meat or bean concoction known as Texas [chili con carne](/Chili_con_carne). While the spelling "chili" is sometimes used outside of New Mexico, U.S. Senator [Pete Domenici](/Pete_Domenici) of New Mexico officially cemented the state's preferred spelling, "chile," by entering it into the [Congressional Record].

One of the earliest proponents of traditional New Mexican cuisine was the educator and writer [Fabiola Cabeza de Baca Gilbert](/Fabiola_Cabeza_de_Baca_Gilbert). Her cookbook, *Historic Cookery*, published in 1931, was instrumental in introducing the art of cooking with [chiles](/Chili_pepper) to a wider American audience.

